----MONITOR-AND-CONTROL-PROCESSES----

MONITOR        : top   ps      pidof
CONTROL        : bg    fg      kill  killall
PRIORITY       : nice  renice
RESOURCE-TRACK : df    du      free 

ps aux : lists all running processes

kill <pid> : kill a process
kill -9 <pid> : force kill 
killall <proc-name> : kill via name (pkill)

EVERY PROCESS START WITH PRIORITY 0 (-20 - 19) :- 
----------------------------------------------
nice -n 15 script.sh : start proc with +15 priority
renice +5 <pid> : update the priority of a process

df : reports the partitions from mount points, (-i) for inode
du : disk usage of each file recursively

Ctrl + Z : suspend (not-running) a task in background             |
jobs -l : see all the suspended tasks (-l pid)                    |-\ close the terminal
fg %1 : bring (resume) the bg-suspended task to fg (%1 job-id)    |-/    process dies
bg %1 : continue a suspended proc in bg                           |
<cmd> & : get the cmd in bg running but dedicated to terminal

disown : to undedicate the terminal
<cmd> & disown : good chain to run the wallpaper loop  #----#

----LINUX-PROC-SIGNALS----

- SIGUP   (1)  : Hangup, often used to tell a daemon to relaod its configuration
- SIGINT  (2)  : Interrupt, by Ctrl-C to terminate
- SIGKILL (9)  : Kill, immediate forcefull termination (kill -9 <pid>)
- SIGSEGV (11) : Segmentation fault, proc made invalid memory reference
- SIGTERM (15) : Termination, polite way to ask a proc to terminate (kill <pid>)
- SIGSTOP      : Stop, pause the process. cannot be caught or ignored
